{"source_key":"sha256-ec49f8107a0d505225a83e69fcc53533","record_index":43,"record_hash":"sha256:f823828a649bc85a6f4e08ddad45bee277b2feff9626089373c08e0d5b8a1dd9","timestamp":"2026-05-11T21:02:43.418Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: a3dd3c\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 943\nOutput:\n     1\t//! Helpers for resolving binary paths.\n     2\t#[cfg(target_os = \"linux\")]\n     3\tuse std::path::Path;\n     4\tuse std::path::PathBuf;\n     5\t\n     6\t/// Resolve the path to the current executable, assuming it's `but`, such that it can be executed.\n     7\t///\n     8\t/// # Linux\n     9\t/// Under Linux, the `/proc/self/exe` magic symlink is maintained by the kernel to point to the\n    10\t/// executable. The kernel keeps the executable's inode alive even if the file has been moved\n    11\t/// or deleted, and therefore this symlink can be executed as long as the process is running.\n    12\t///\n    13\t/// Resolving the symlink with [`std::env::current_exe`] fully resolves `/proc/self/exe` to the\n    14\t/// executable it points to. Executing that fails if the binary has been removed. This is the case\n    15\t/// when emitting metrics for the `update install` command. The executable first renames itself\n    16\t/// (causing `/proc/self/exe` to point to the new location) and then removes itself once the new\n    17\t/// version is successfully installed (causing `/proc/self/exe` to point to a non-existing binary).\n    18\t///\n    19\t/// As [`std::env::current_exe`] resolves the symlink, it also means that the `but ->\n    20\t/// gitbutler-tauri` symlink trick to execute the CLI via the primary `gitbutler-tauri` executable\n    21\t/// fails, as it's executed with the fully resolved path.\n    22\t///\n    23\t/// Note that both of the above issues could _probably_ be addressed by using argv[0] as the path,\n    24\t/// but as we are always guaranteed to have `/proc/self/exe` we might as well use it.\n    25\t///\n    26\t/// # Windows and macOS\n    27\t/// Under macOS and Windows, there's no equivalent to Linux's /proc/self/exe, so we\n    28\t/// can't easily refer to the \"current process' program\" like we can there.\n    29\t///\n    30\t/// On macOS, std::env::current_exe() is implemented with _NSGetExecutablePath, which provides the\n    31\t/// path the executable was launched with. In the `update install` case, metrics will then be\n    32\t/// emitted with the _new_ version rather than the one that actually ran the command. The only way\n    33\t/// around this is to emit metrics before cleaning up the old version, but that does not seem\n    34\t/// worthwhile at the moment.\n    35\t///\n    36\t/// On Windows, current_exe() is implemented with GetModuleFileNameW, which also\n    37\t/// returns the path with which the executable was launched, and so has the same\n    38\t/// problem. Although at the time of writing, `update install` is not implemented\n    39\t/// for Windows.\n    40\tpub fn current_exe_for_but_exec() -> std::io::Result<PathBuf> {\n    41\t    #[cfg(target_os = \"linux\")]\n    42\t    {\n    43\t        Ok(\"/proc/self/exe\".into())\n    44\t    }\n    45\t    #[cfg(not(target_os = \"linux\"))]\n    46\t    {\n    47\t        std::env::current_exe()\n    48\t    }\n    49\t}\n    50\t\n    51\t/// Determine if this program was executed with the intention of running the `but` CLI, handling the\n    52\t/// case where this may be `gitbutler-tauri` invoked via symlink.\n    53\tpub fn is_executed_as_but() -> anyhow::Result<bool> {\n    54\t    #[cfg(target_os = \"linux\")]\n    55\t    {\n    56\t        Ok(std::env::args_os().next().is_some_and(|exec_path| {\n    57\t            // Assumption: We never self-exec the GUI itself\n    58\t            exec_path == \"/proc/self/exe\"\n    59\t                || Path::new(&exec_path)\n    60\t                    .file_stem()\n    61\t                    .is_some_and(|stem| stem == \"but\")\n    62\t        }))\n    63\t    }\n    64\t    #[cfg(not(target_os = \"linux\"))]\n    65\t    {\n    66\t        let current_exe = std::env::current_exe()?;\n    67\t        Ok(current_exe.file_stem().is_some_and(|stem| stem == \"but\"))\n    68\t    }\n    69\t}\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T21:02:43.418Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}